# Project 2 - Improved Multi-server Network

## Introduction

This is an advanced version of project 1 which provides:

- High Available
- Eventually Consistancy


## How to start this system

### Basic start script

Check full parameter specification [here](#Script Parameter Instructure) if you want.

A shortcut script to build a system with 5 servers  and 4 users is [here](#Shortcut)

##### Server

- Start the very first server

```bash
java -jar Server-jar-with-dependencies.jar -lh localhost -lp 8001 -s abc
```

- New servers joining the system

```bash
# Connect to 8001 server with system secret
java -jar Server-jar-with-dependencies.jar -lh localhost -lp 8002 -s abc -rh localhost -rp 8001
# Connect to 8001 server with system secret
java -jar Server-jar-with-dependencies.jar -lh localhost -lp 8003 -s abc -rh localhost -rp 8001 
# Connect to 8002 server with system secret
java -jar Server-jar-with-dependencies.jar -lh localhost -lp 8004 -s abc -rh localhost -rp 8002
# Connect to 8004 server with system secret
java -jar Server-jar-with-dependencies.jar -lh localhost -lp 8005 -s abc -rh localhost -rp 8004
# Connect to 8004 server with system secret
java -jar Server-jar-with-dependencies.jar -lh localhost -lp 8006 -s abc -rh localhost -rp 8004 
```

In this way, a network will be established.

For every server, a UI will show up to indicate the information of login users, registered users, existing connections and log.

##### Client

- User register (user will automatically login after registeration)

```bash
# Register user named 'ningk' at server 8001
java -jar Client-jar-with-dependencies.jar -u ningk -rp 8001 -rh localhost 

# Register user named 'yirupan' at server 8002
java -jar Client-jar-with-dependencies.jar -u yirupan -rp 8002 -rh localhost

# Register user named 'nannangu' at server 8002
java -jar Client-jar-with-dependencies.jar -u nannangu -rp 8002 -rh localhost 

# Register user named 'wenyizhao' at server 8005
java -jar Client-jar-with-dependencies.jar -u wenyizhao -rp 8005 -rh localhost
```

This login will make the network like this:

A UI will show up which allows user to send activity and receive message from server.

- User login (If you logout and want to relogin )

Note that users who are already registered can login from any server.

```bash
# Login user named 'ningk' at server 8003 (instead of 8001 which this id registers at)
java -jar Client-jar-with-dependencies.jar -u ningk -rp 8003 -rh localhost -s $secret1

# Login user named 'yirupan' at server 8001 (instead of 8002 which this id registers at)
java -jar Client-jar-with-dependencies.jar -u yirupan -rp 8001 -rh localhost -s $secret1

# Login user named 'nannangu' at server 8004 (instead of 8002 which this id registers at)
java -jar Client-jar-with-dependencies.jar -u nannangu -rp 8004 -rh localhost -s $secret1

# Login user named 'wenyizhao' at server 8002 (instead of 8005 which this id registers at)
java -jar Client-jar-with-dependencies.jar -u wenyizhao -rp 8002 -rh localhost -s $secret1
```



## Test cases 

- High Available

If you **force quit** a server(*like click close icon in server UI or press CTRL+C in command line*), let's say server 8004, then server 8002,8005,8006 will pick as the backup server for 8004, say 8002,  and other servers(8005, 8006) will reconnect to this server (8002).

- Message ensure

Build a simple system with steps:

1. Start the very frist server

```bash
java -jar Server-jar-with-dependencies.jar -lh localhost -lp 8001 -s abc
```

2. Start a new server (8003) connect to 8001

```bash
java -jar Server-jar-with-dependencies.jar -lh localhost -lp 8001 -s abc
```

3. start a client connect to 8003

```bash
java -jar Client-jar-with-dependencies.jar -u ningk -rp 8003 -rh localhost 
```

4. Use `telnet` to simulate a server

```bash
telent localhost 8001
# copy & paste below string to telnet command line
{"command":"AUTHENTICATE","serverid":"abcdefg","secret":"abc","host":"localhost","port":"1"}
# then telent will receive a sync message, and then backup list/server announce every 5s
```

5. Terminate server 8001, using CTRL+C in command line

6. Check the BACKUP_LIST in telnet, if the first one of the list is

   

- Message order


- Client can join and leave any time

Just close client ui and restart client with registered username and secret. A user registers at one server can login to all servers of this system

- Server can join at any time

Start a server at any time, even if some users have already registered/logined. The new-join server will automatically sync these kind of data with existing system.

- 
- Load balancing

Try to login to a server which load=1

### Script Parameter Instructure



```bash
usage: ActivityStreamer.Server [-a <arg>] [-lh <arg>] [-lp <arg>] [-rh
       <arg>] [-rp <arg>] [-s <arg>]
An ActivityStream Server for Unimelb COMP90015

 -a  <arg>   activity interval in milliseconds;Optional, default value = "5000"
 -lh <arg>   local hostname; Optional, default value="localhost"
 -lp <arg>   local port number; Optional, default value="3780"
 -rh <arg>   remote hostname; Optional for the very first server and Mandantory for new coming servers.
 -rp <arg>   remote port number;OPtional, default value="3780"
 -s  <arg>    secret for the server to use; Optional, program will generate one if is not provided.
```



### Client Setup

```bash
usage: ActivityStreamer.Client [-rh <arg>] [-rp <arg>] [-s
       <arg>] [-u <arg>]
An ActivityStream Client for Unimelb COMP90015
 -rh <arg>   remote hostname
 -rp <arg>   remote port number
 -s  <arg>   secret for username, if not provided, run "register" process
 -u  <arg>   username, if not provided, login as "anonymous".
```

This login will make the network like this:
